{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> σμύρνα</b>, <br /> frequently written <b>ζμύρνα</b> as in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “PSI” 4.328.2 (3rd c.BC), “PTeb.” 35.4 (2nd c.BC), “PMag.Par.” 1.781, etc., ἡ,= μύρρα\">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>], <b>myrrh</b>, the gum of an Arabian tree, <b>Balsamodendron Myrrha</b> (itself called σμύρνα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Apollodorus Damascenus Mechanicus 3.14.4, 2nd c.AD(?): Antoninus Liberalis Mythographus 34.5)\">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>], used for embalming the dead, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 2.40, 86, compare 73, NT.John.19.39 \">NT+5th c.BC+</a>]; called σμύρνης ἱδρώς by [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Ion” 1175 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; burnt as incense, βωμὸς ἀτμίζων πυρὶ σμύρνης σταλαγμούς [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Fragmenta” 370 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ὑποθυμιῆν σ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Hippocrates Medicus “περὶ γυναικείης φύσιος” 6 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; used as an unguent or salve, σμύρνῃ κατάλειπτος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Equites” 1332; σμύρνῃ ἰώμενοι τὰ ἕλκεα 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 7.181; compare 4th-3rd c.BC: Theophrastus Philosophus “Historia Plantarum” 9.1.2, 9.4.3 and 10, 1st c.AD: Dioscorides (Dioscurides) Medicus 1.64, etc. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> <b>Indian bdellium, Balsamodendron Mukul</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Arrianus Historicus “Anabasis” 6.22.4. (The originally form must have been μύρρα, from 3rd c.BC: Phoenix Iambographus \">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>] <b>môrâh</b>; compare κιννάμωμον.)","strongNumber":"G4666","accentedUnicode":"σμύρνα","relatedNos":[{"strongNumber":"G3464","matchingForm":"μύρον","stepTransliteration":"muron","gloss":"ointment","_zh_tw_Gloss":"香膏","_es_Gloss":"ungüento","_zh_Gloss":"香膏"},{"strongNumbe